    ğŸ”¹ `-l<library>` --> ğŸ“š Links the specified library (e.g., `-lm` for the math library).
    ğŸ”¹ `-L<path>`   --> ğŸ§­ Adds a path where `ld.bfd` should search for libraries.
    ğŸ”¹ `-static`    --> ğŸ”— Links libraries statically.
    ğŸ”¹ `-shared`    --> ğŸ”— Links libraries as shared.
    ğŸ”¹ `-rpath <path>` --> ğŸ›£ï¸ Embeds a path in the executable to search for shared libraries at runtime.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ ld.bfd -o myprogram main.o utils.o

    ğŸ”¹ Links the `main.o` and `utils.o` files and creates an executable named `myprogram`.

    $ ld.bfd -o myprogram main.o -lm

    ğŸ”¹ Links the `main.o` file and also links the math library (`libm.so`).

âœ… **Simple Example:**

    $ ld.bfd -o hello hello.o -lc

    ğŸ”¹ Links the object file `hello.o` with the C standard library (`libc.so`) to create an executable named `hello`. This `hello` file is ready to execute and utilizes C standard library functions.
